******
[1] Chile (national, BioBio region)
Date: Sun 8 Apr 2012
Source: BioBio Chile [in Spanish, trans & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.biobiochile.cl/2012/04/08/autoridades-insisten-en-llamado-a-tomar-medidas-preventivas-contra-el-virus-hanta.shtml


Statistics from the Institute of Public Health [indicate] that 37 cases of [a] hantavirus infection occurred nationally so far this season [2012], 11 of which resulted in death.

The BioBio province has not been a stranger to the fatal statistics, with 2 people [dead] this year [2012], one of the cases in the Tucapel community and the other in Mulchen. The health authority reiterated its call to the populace to consider preventive measures [against contracting the infection].

[Published by Erasmo Tauran; information from Luis Villegas]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Although not specified, the hantavirus involved in this fatal case and the following ones is most likely Andes virus.

An image of the long-tailed pygmy rice rat (_Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_), the sigmodontine rodent host of Andes hantavirus, can be seen at http://www.bios.niu.edu/frayjorge/rod6.jpg).

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Chile can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/00Bj. - Mod.TY]

******
[2] Chile (Maule region)
Date: Thu 5 Apr 2012
Source: EMOL [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.emol.com/noticias/nacional/2012/04/05/534520/confirman-nueva-muerte-por-virus-hanta-victima-se-contagio-en-la-region-del-maule.html


A young man died after becoming infected with [a] hantavirus in the Maujle region, bringing to 11 the number of fatal victims due to the disease so far this year [2012]. The patient who lost his life was 19 years old and had acquired the virus [infection] in an area near Lake Colbun, according to the Institute of Public Health [ISP]. The area where the infection was acquired is the Mirador Las Vizcachas sector, according to Radio Cooperativo.

In the entire country, 37 hantavirus [infection] cases have been registered in 2012. This year [2012], the ISP put into action a system that includes the use of the ELISA test for rapid diagnosis of the disease through specialized laboratories distributed around the country.

Hantavirus enters the body via the respiratory route. It is present in the excrement of infected wild long-tailed mice [long-tailed pygmy rice rats, _Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_], so the main preventive measure is to avoid places that have remained closed and weedy areas that might be used by these rodents.

--
